26. certe enim, ‘ yes, I know for certain.’ Enim in old Latin often had an affirmative force, something like nempe, with which enim is etymologically connected. The illative force is latent, but it is going too far, in my opinion, to deny the existence of this illative or causal force in Plautus. Instances of the affirmative use are Plaut. Most. 3. l. 24, Quid tuce tecum? TRA. Nihil enim (‘why, nothing’); Cas. 2. 5. 15, Quid tu postea? OL. Nessea-2· enim ipsi nze concessurum Iovi. Ussing quotes Ter. See Tyrrell's Note on Mil. 4. 6. 6 ; Brix on Trin. 3. 2. 79: it is especially used in the phrases at enim, quia enim, non enim, nihil enim, certe enim, enim vero, enim iam.
